                <head>From the Vindicator</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Reprints a letter written to the Vindicator from an unnamed soldier and
                    originally published in the June 19th edition of the newspaper. The soldier
                    accused the editor of the Spectator of criticizing certain officers of the
                    Confederate army and then fleeing to Lewisburg when Yankee troops were nearby
                    rather than staying to protect his and his neighbors' property. The editor of
                    the Spectator responds with two columns of refutation.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <pageNote>Also on this page are a reprinted list of deserters from the 52nd Regiment of
                Virginia Volunteers, sections eleven through eighteen of the tax act approved on
                April 24, 1863, an article comparing Napoleon's great battles with those of recent
                times, and war news.</pageNote>
        </page>
